10.2.1

mpg |> 
  ggplot() + 
  geom_point(aes(x = hwy, y = displ), shape = 24, fill = "pink")

The color = "blue" needs to be moved out of aes when it is set to a value instead of mapped to a variable.

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = "blue"))

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy), color = "blue")

Stroke sets the width of the border (if your shape has a border).

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ < 5))

10.3.1

geom_line() for a line, geom_boxplot() for a boxplot, geom_area() for an area plot.

show.legend = FALSE hides the geom from the legend. This was used previously to maintain the regular plot shape to ease comparison (otherwise legend shrinks the plot area).

se plots the confidence interval of geom_smooth().

Going per row, from left to right:

mpg |> #1
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

mpg |> #2
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(aes(group = drv), se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

mpg |> #3
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv, color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

mpg |> #4
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(group = drv, color = drv)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

mpg |> #5
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv, linetype = drv)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = drv)) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

mpg |> #6
  ggplot(aes(x = displ, y = hwy, group = drv, linetype = drv)) + 
  geom_point(aes(fill = drv), shape = 21, color = "white", stroke = 2 )

10.4.1

mpg |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = hwy, y = displ)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~cty)

It means that the specific drv and cyl combination is not existing in the data.

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = drv, y = cyl))

It controls whether the variable will be displayed side-by-side or stacked.

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

For larger data sets, color gets busy and, unless specified, is only recommeded for six separate group members (colors).

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

ncolor nrow controls facet_wrap() plot layout, and is inteded for use with a single variable with many levels. Instead, facet_grid() is intended for facetting two separate variables against eachother in a matrix layout.

It is much easier to compare when they are stacked.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ)) + 
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_grid(. ~ drv)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(mpg) + 
  geom_point(aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_wrap(~drv, ncol = 1, strip.position = "right")

10.5.1

diamonds |>
  summarise(
    min = min(depth),
    max = max(depth),
    median = median(depth),
    .by = cut
  ) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = cut, y = median)) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = min, ymax = max))

geom_col uses stat_identity instead of stat_count (default for geom_bar), it is therefore advisable to use geom_col when you want to plot the values.

stat_smooth calculates the following variables (x or y, depending on orientation):

  • after_stat(x), the predicted value.
  • after_stat(xmin), lower pointwise confidence interval around the mean.
  • after_stat(xmax), upper pointwise confidence interval around the mean.
  • after_stat(se), standard error.

The difference can be seen if plotted:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, y = after_stat(prop))) + 
  geom_bar()

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = after_stat(prop))) + 
  geom_bar()

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, y = after_stat(prop), group = 1)) + 
  geom_bar()

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = cut, fill = color, y = after_stat(prop), group = 1)) + 
  geom_bar()
## Warning: The following aesthetics were dropped during statistical transformation: fill
## â„¹ This can happen when ggplot fails to infer the correct grouping structure in
##   the data.
## â„¹ Did you forget to specify a `group` aesthetic or to convert a numerical
##   variable into a factor?

After setting group to 1, the proportion is calculated across all the different cuts - as opossed to running proportion for each cut.
